---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Start Here">
  <div class="page-head">
    <span class="eyebrow">Orientation</span>
    <h1>Start here</h1>
    <p class="standfirst">
      What Econschool is, and a sensible path through it.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>What this is</h2>
  <p>
    Econschool is a free learning resource for economics and the mathematics under
    it — the material that serious study assumes. Lectures, courses, and solved
    problems, with the full working shown throughout.
  </p>
  <p>
    Nearly everything here is free: the
    <a href="https://www.youtube.com/@econ.school">lectures on YouTube</a>, the
    <a href="/courses/">courses</a>, the <a href="/problems/">problem library</a>,
    and the <a href="/resources/">resources</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>A sensible path</h2>
  <p>
    The courses are meant to be worked through in order: the mathematics first,
    then probability and statistics, then economics itself. More are being added
    over time; start with what is there and build up.
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Learn from the courses and lectures.</strong> Begin with the
      <a href="/courses/">mathematics</a>. Each lesson pairs a video with written
      notes, worked at the level graduate study assumes.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Solve, with your own hands.</strong> Pick problems from the
      <a href="/problems/">library</a>. Attempt every exercise unaided before reading
      any solution — the struggle is where the learning is.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Check your working line by line.</strong> Solved problems here show
      every step, so you can find where your attempt diverged.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Go deeper when ready.</strong> The research-to-problem series turns
      major papers into problems you can solve yourself.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <h2>How to read this site</h2>
  <p>
    Color is notation here, as in all Econschool materials: in every diagram, blue
    is person 1, red is person 2, green marks Pareto-efficient sets, and orange
    marks equilibria and endowments. Once you know the convention, you can read a
    new diagram at a glance.
  </p>
  <p>
    Mathematics is set properly throughout. If a step looks compressed, it isn't —
    every solved problem shows the full working.
  </p>

  <h2>Stay in the loop</h2>
  <p>
    New problems, videos, and courses are posted under
    <a href="/announcements/">News</a>. That page is the single place to check.
  </p>
</Layout>